subtropical Queensland. Well-suited to Brisbane climate.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 21}, {"name": "Variety B (Australian Rose)", "slug": "variety-b-australian-rose", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Northern NSW lowland/floodplain areas", "traits": "Rare small tree, extremely pleasant lemony aromatic foliage", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Brisbane-suitable subtropical plant. Three chemotypes exist. Lemon-scented foliage when crushed. Limited commercial availability.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 22}, {"name": "Standard Form", "slug": "standard-form", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Eastern Australia coastal regions", "traits": "Shrub/small tree to 6m, shredding bark", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Grows naturally on beach sand. Excellent Brisbane coastal conditions tolerance. Used for erosion control. Frost-hardy to -10°C.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 23}, {"name": "Terpinen-4-ol Chemotype", "slug": "terpinen-4-ol-chemotype", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Australian, cultivated in India (Kolenchery, Kerala area)", "traits": "Small tree to 7m, bushy crown, narrow needle-like leaves, papery bark", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Successfully cultivated in Kerala tropical monsoon climate. Grows well in humid subtropical to tropical areas with 800-1600mm annual rainfall. Prefers frost-free areas (annual lows 9-21°C, highs 22-35°C). Essential oil production established in India. Adapts to Kerala''s hot, humid conditions. Requires well-drained moist soils.", "availability": "Limited; specialty nurseries, commercial oil plantations", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "Standard Form", "slug": "standard-form", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Northern Australia, extending to Southeast Asia (Malaysia, Indonesia)", "traits": "Large tree to 20m+, weeping branches, thick white/pinkish papery bark", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Known as ''gelam'' in Malaysia. Naturally occurs in Southeast Asian swamp forests. Well-adapted to tropical monsoon climates like Kerala. Tolerates waterlogged conditions and seasonal flooding. Source of cajuput-type essential oil. Traditional uses in Malaysia for timber and oil.", "availability": "May be available through botanical gardens or specialty imports", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "Subspecies cajuputi", "slug": "subspecies-cajuputi", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, Vietnam (naturalized)", "traits": "Medium-large tree to 35m, white/grey-white papery bark (kayu putih = white wood)", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Native to tropical Asia, including regions with similar climate to Kerala. Grows in coastal swamp forests. Excellent adaptation to tropical monsoon conditions with heavy rainfall. Commercial source of cajuput oil widely used in Southeast Asia. Traditional medicinal uses for infections, respiratory issues.", "availability": "Potentially available in Kerala through Asian trade networks or botanical gardens", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "Subspecies cumingiana", "slug": "subspecies-cumingiana", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia (Sumatra, Java, Kalimantan)", "traits": "Leaves 40-200mm long x 10-20mm wide, 7-9 stamens per bundle", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Southeast Asian coastal swamp forest native. Suited to Kerala''s tropical monsoon climate. Flowering February-December.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "Standard Form", "slug": "standard-form", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "New Caledonia, Papua New Guinea, coastal eastern Australia", "traits": "Tree 8-25m, thick papery bark, leaves 40-70mm with 5 veins", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Grows in tropical to subtropical climates (similar latitude to Kerala). Tolerates swamps, floodplains, wet soils. Vigorously resprouts after fire. Cultivated as ornamental in tropical regions worldwide. Produces niaouli essential oil. May adapt to Kerala monsoon conditions but requires monitoring as can become invasive.", "availability": "Potentially available as ornamental, use with caution due to invasive potential", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "Standard Form", "slug": "standard-form", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Northern Australia", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Dominant species in northern Australian melaleuca forests. High antibacterial activity in essential oil. May adapt to Kerala''s monsoon rainfall patterns. Similar to M. cajuputi in tropical adaptation.", "availability": "Limited; research/botanical collections", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "L. amboinense", "slug": "l-amboinense", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Queensland to Southeast Asia", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Most likely Leptospermum species for Kerala. Extends from Queensland through Southeast Asian tropical regions. May tolerate Kerala''s tropical monsoon climate better than temperate Leptospermum species.", "availability": "Very limited; botanical collections", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "L. javanicum", "slug": "l-javanicum", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Southeast Asia (Java)", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Southeast Asian endemic. Potential Kerala adaptation due to similar tropical climate. Rare.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "L. parviflorum", "slug": "l-parviflorum", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Southeast Asia", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Southeast Asian endemic. Possible Kerala cultivation but very limited information available.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 8}], "variety_count": 33}'::jsonb,
  variety_count = 33, status = 'parsed'
WHERE source_path = 'brainstorm-inbox/import-payloads/tea-tree.json';

UPDATE public.garden_import_queue SET payload = '{"species": "Teak", "species_slug": "teak", "varieties": [{"name": "1. Australian Teak / Crow''s Ash (Flindersia australis) 🏆", "slug": "1-australian-teak-crow-s-ash-flindersia-australis", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to Queensland and New South Wales, Australia (pre-1788)", "traits": "Large semi-deciduous tree, 30-40m tall, compound leaves with 5-13 leaflets, scaly brown bark, fast-growing", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Reaches 3-6m in 12 years with good conditions. Can exceed 40m at maturity.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Widely available at Queensland nurseries including Daley''s Fruit Tree Nursery (Pullenvale), Aussie Tree Care (Gold Coast), Sequoia Valley Farms, The Diggers Club", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "2. Queensland Silver Ash (Flindersia australis local form) 🏆", "slug": "2-queensland-silver-ash-flindersia-australis-local-form", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Queensland-specific ecotype, selected for silver-grey bark characteristics", "traits": "Distinguished by distinctive silver-grey bark color, compound glossy green leaves, spotted bark appearance from flaking", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Queensland native plant nurseries, local council tree programs", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "3. New Guinea Teak Plantations", "slug": "3-new-guinea-teak-plantations", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Papua New Guinea plantation-grown Tectona grandis", "traits": "Golden-brown heartwood with grey/red tinges, straight grain, high natural oil content, ''greasy'' feel", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available as timber through Brisbane suppliers like Narangba Timbers, Paradise Timbers. Seedlings/plants rarely available locally.", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "4. Burmese Teak (Myanmar Provenance) 🏆", "slug": "4-burmese-teak-myanmar-provenance", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Myanmar (Burma) natural forests, considered world''s highest quality teak", "traits": "Rich golden-brown heartwood, exceptionally high oil content, tight grain, high silica content (from sandy Myanmar soils)", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available only as imported timber, not as plants in Australia", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "5. Indonesian Teak (Plantation) 🧬", "slug": "5-indonesian-teak-plantation", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Java, Indonesia - sustainable plantations, FSC-certified sources available", "traits": "Light golden to medium brown, tight grain, moderate oil content (lower than Burmese), influenced by volcanic soil minerals", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available as imported timber through Queensland suppliers", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "1. Nilambur Teak (തേക്ക്/Thekku) 🏆", "slug": "1-nilambur-teak-thekku", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Nilambur, Malappuram District, Kerala - World''s first teak plantation (1842-1846)", "traits": "Exceptional size (up to 50m height, 2.5m diameter), rich mahogany-golden brown color, distinctive grain pattern. Tree No. 23 in Conolly''s Plot: 4.29m girth, 49.2m length - world''s largest plantation teak.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "At Nilambur: 6.93m height, 6.3cm dbh at 5 years; 22.83m height, 45.85cm dbh at 50 years. Significant growth acceleration after 30 years.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Nilambur Teak Nursery (est. 2004), Kerala Forest Department nurseries, select Kerala private nurseries. Seeds collected from superior mother trees along Chaliyar River.", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "2. Kannimara Teak (World''s Oldest) 🏆", "slug": "2-kannimara-teak-world-s-oldest", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Parambikulam Wildlife Sanctuary, Palakkad District, Kerala", "traits": "Ancient growth form, massive buttressed trunk, exceptional heartwood quality due to extreme age", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Protected specimen, not available for propagation. Genetic material preserved at Kerala Forest Research Institute.", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "3. Travancore Teak 🏆", "slug": "3-travancore-teak", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Historical Travancore region (Southern Kerala: Thiruvananthapuram, Kollam, Pathanamthitta districts)", "traits": "Similar to Nilambur teak but adapted to higher rainfall areas of southern Western Ghats", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Kerala Forest Department seed production areas, Kollam district nurseries", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "4. Ranni Teak", "slug": "4-ranni-teak", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Ranni forest division, Pathanamthitta District (near Thiruvalla)", "traits": "Locally recognized as ''second best'' teak in Kerala after Nilambur. High-quality timber from natural forests.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Limited - natural forest provenance. Contact Pathanamthitta Forest Division for authorized seed sources.", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "5. Konni Teak 🏆", "slug": "5-konni-teak", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Konni, Pathanamthitta District - Kerala''s first Reserve Forest (1888)", "traits": "Medium-elevation teak adapted to Western Ghats foothill conditions", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Kerala Forest Department - Pathanamthitta Division nurseries", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "6. Malayattoor Teak", "slug": "6-malayattoor-teak", "lineage_type": "heirlo